# Milli: AI-Enabled nano

Milli is a terminal text editor built on GNU nano, with the same Pico-like feel plus AI assists (Alt+1/Alt+2), syntax highlighting, undo/redo, multiple buffers, softwrap, regex search/replace, and more. It is still nano at heart—licensed under GPLv3+, with documentation under the GFDL 1.2+ (two busybox functions remain BSD-licensed).

## Appearance

```
 ____________________________________________________________________
|  Milli 8.7                     filename                  Modified  |
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
| Text window shows the current buffer.                             |
| Title bar shows version/name/state; status line shows feedback.   |
| Two bottom rows list shortcuts (^=Ctrl, M-=Alt/Meta).              |
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
| [ Some status message ]                                           |
|^G Help   ^O Write Out  ^F Where Is   ^K Cut     ^T Execute         |
|^X Exit   ^R Read File  ^\ Replace    ^U Paste   M-1 AI Replace     |
|                                  M-2 AI Insert   ^J Justify        |
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
```

## Quick start (build from git)
No release tarballs yet; build from the repo:
```sh
git clone https://github.com/manimohans/milli.git
cd milli
./autogen.sh
./configure --enable-debug
make
sudo make install
```

Build deps: ncurses headers (`libncurses-dev` on Debian/Ubuntu, `ncurses-devel` on Fedora/RHEL), gettext, autoconf, automake, pkg-config, make, gcc/clang. Use `--prefix` to install elsewhere (e.g., `./configure --prefix=$HOME/.local && make && make install`) and ensure the chosen bin dir is on `PATH`. Sample syntax/options live in `doc/sample.nanorc` (copy to `~/.nanorc`).

## AI configuration (OpenAI-compatible endpoints)

Milli reads `~/.milli.config` at startup. Copy `doc/milli.config.example` and adjust:
```
base_url = http://127.0.0.1:1234        # no /v1 here
responses_endpoint = /v1/responses
models_endpoint = /v1/models
model = google/gemma-3-1b
api_key = lm-studio   # use a real key for OpenAI Cloud
temperature = 0.2
timeout_ms = 60000
```
- Alt+1 (AI Replace): select text, press Alt+1, enter a prompt; selection is replaced.
- Alt+2 (AI Insert): press Alt+2, enter a prompt; text inserts at the cursor.
- LM Studio accepts any bearer token; OpenAI Cloud requires a valid key.

## Upstream, license, and support

- Upstream project: https://nano-editor.org/ (Milli is a downstream of GNU nano).
- Mailing lists (upstream): info-nano@gnu.org, help-nano@gnu.org, nano-devel@gnu.org.
- Bugs: include “Milli” when filing at https://savannah.gnu.org/bugs/?group=nano or emailing nano-devel.
- Licensing: GPLv3+ for code (except two BSD-licensed busybox functions); documentation under GFDL 1.2+. See `COPYING` and `COPYING.DOC`.
